  "statement": {
    "markdown": "Given an integer `n`, generate all possible combinations of well-formed parentheses of length `2 * n`. A well-formed combination of parentheses is one that satisfies the following conditions:\n\n- An open parenthesis can be placed before any unmatched close parenthesis.\n- A close parenthesis can be placed after a matching open parenthesis.",
    "inputFormat": "N\nn",
    "outputFormat": "variable number of lines, each line is a string of parentheses\n... (multiple lines)",
    "notes": "",
    "images": [],
    "constraints": [
      {
        "variable": "n",
        "type": "integer",
        "min": 1,
        "max": 8,
        "description": "The number of pairs of parentheses."
      }
    ],
    "examples": [
      {
        "input": "3",
        "output": "((()))\r\n(()())\r\n(())()\r\n()(())\r\n()()()",
        "explanation": "For n = 3, the output should contain all possible well-formed combinations of 3 pairs of parentheses."
      },
      {
        "input": "1",
        "output": "()",
        "explanation": "For n = 1, the output should contain the only possible well-formed combination of 1 pair of parentheses."
      }
    ]
  },
  "hints": [
    {
      "order": 1,
      "text": "This problem can be solved using backtracking, where you try to add an open parenthesis and then a close parenthesis, but remember that you can only add a close parenthesis after an open parenthesis."
    },
    {
      "order": 2,
      "text": "You can use a recursive function to generate all possible combinations, and to keep track of the current combination you can use a string or a list of characters."
    },
    {
      "order": 3,
      "text": "You should start with an empty string or list, and then in each recursive call, you can choose to add an open parenthesis or a close parenthesis, but remember that you can only add a close parenthesis after an open parenthesis."
    },
    {
      "order": 4,
      "text": "You should also keep track of the number of open and close parentheses that you have added, and make sure that the number of open parentheses is always greater than or equal to the number of close parentheses."
    },
    {
      "order": 5,
      "text": "Finally, when you have added `n` open and `n` close parentheses, you have found a well-formed combination of parentheses, so you should add it to the result."
    }
  ],
  "editorial": {
    "title": "Generating Balanced Parentheses: From Exhaustive Search to Catalan‑Driven Backtracking",
    "intuition": "The heart of the problem is that at every step we must decide whether to place an opening or a closing parenthesis, but only under two safety rules: we cannot exceed the total number of pairs, and we cannot close more than we have opened. These constraints prune the search tree dramatically, leaving exactly the Catalan number of valid strings.",
    "bruteForce": "A naïve brute force would generate all 2^(2n) binary strings of length 2n, interpreting 0 as '(' and 1 as ')', and then filter those that are balanced. While correct, this approach explodes exponentially: for n=8 we already produce 65536 candidates, most of which are discarded. The time cost is O(2^(2n)) and the space cost is dominated by storing all candidates before filtering, making it infeasible even for modest n.",
    "betterSolution": "The key observation is that a valid string can be built incrementally: at any point we may add '(' if we still have unused pairs, and we may add ')' only if it would not make the string invalid. This leads to a depth‑first search that explores only legal prefixes, automatically discarding impossible branches. The recursion depth never exceeds 2n, and each leaf corresponds to one valid combination.",
    "optimalSolution": "The optimal backtracking algorithm maintains two counters: the number of '(' used so far (open) and the number of ')' used (close). It recurses only when open < n (add '(') and when close < open (add ')'). When the string reaches length 2n, it is appended to the result list. This generates exactly the Catalan(n) strings in O(Catalan(n)) time and uses O(Catalan(n)·n) space for the output plus O(n) stack space.",
    "proofOfCorrectness": "The algorithm constructs strings by appending characters that keep the prefix balanced. The invariant \"close ≤ open ≤ n\" holds at every recursive call. Adding '(' preserves the invariant because open increases but never exceeds n. Adding ')' preserves it because we only add when close < open, so after the addition close < open+1 ≤ n. When the string length is 2n, we have used exactly n of each parenthesis, and the invariant guarantees that the entire string is balanced. Conversely, any balanced string can be produced by this process: reading the string left to right, each '(' increases open, each ')' decreases close, and the conditions of the algorithm are satisfied at every step. Thus the algorithm enumerates all and only the valid strings.",
    "dryRun": "For n=3 the recursion tree starts with \"\". It first adds '(' → \"(\" (open=1,close=0). From there it can add '(' → \"((\" (2,0) or ')' → \"(\"? no, close<open so add ')' → \"()\" (1,1). Continuing this way, the algorithm explores all valid prefixes and finally outputs: \"((()))\",\"(()())\",\"(())()\",\"()(())\",\"()()()\". Each leaf is reached exactly once, and no invalid string is produced.",
    "commonMistakes": [
      "Assuming that the order of generated strings matters; the problem only requires a set, so any order is fine.",
      "Trying to generate all 2^(2n) strings and then filter, leading to timeouts.",
      "Forgetting to reset the recursion stack properly, causing memory leaks in languages with manual memory management.",
      "Misinterpreting the condition for adding ')' as close <= open instead of close < open, which allows premature closing and invalid strings.",
      "Using a global counter for open/close instead of passing them as parameters, leading to shared state across recursive branches.",
      "Not handling the base case correctly (e.g., checking length==n instead of length==2*n)."
    ],
    "timeComplexity": "O(Catalan(n)) where Catalan(n) is the number of valid combinations, each of length 2n",
    "spaceComplexity": "O(Catalan(n) * n) for storing results plus O(n) recursion stack"
  },
